articles.title: Arek Chouzadjian Blog
articles.description: Welcome to the website. I hope you enjoy it!
articles.contents:
Blog Post 1: COVID-19 pandemic in Panama
This blog post focuses on the COVID-19 pandemic in Panama. The following analysis focuses on two aspects of the pandemic:
How cases and deaths in Panama have fluctuated from month to month.
How the Death Rate from COVID-19 in Panama has fluctuated from month to month, and the implications that measure has for health system capability, and vaccine coverage/efficacy.


Data description
The dataset is sourced from the coronavirus package, which is either installed from the CRAN, or is installed directly from GitHub (github.com/RamiKrispin/coronavirus). In this case, I have installed the package from GitHub directly, so as to access the most recent data. The raw data in the package is pulled from the Johns Hopkins University Centre for Systems Science and Engineering Coronavirus repository.
The dataset contains data on COVID-19 confirmed cases, deaths and recoveries in each country, from January 22 2020, to 27 August 2021. It also contains the latitude and longitude for each country. As I am only focusing on Panama, I can forego a description of the country, latitude and longitude variables. The Panama COVID-19 data features three important variables - date, type and cases.
The variable ‘date’ is a date variable that contains each date, from 22 January 2020, to 27 August 2021, in ymd format.
The variable ‘type’ is a character variable that contains three levels - ‘confirmed’, ‘death’ and ‘recovered’. ‘Confirmed’ refers to total cases on any given day, ‘death’ refers to total deaths on any given day, and ‘recovered’ refers to the total number of recovered cases reported on any given day.
The variable ‘cases’ is a numeric variable that contains the number of confirmed cases, deaths or recoveries for each day.

The dataset that is downloaded through the coronavirus package is in a largely tidy format, so not much data wrangling is required. It is very easy to use.
Monthly confirmed cases, deaths, and the monthly death rate:
The first table included in this post is an interactive table, created using the DT package, that features confirmed cases of, and deaths from, COVID-19 in Panama. It also contains a calculation of the Death Rate per month, which is just the number of deaths per months divided by the number of cases, multiplied by 100.

The Death Rate variable I have included is the same as the Case Fatality Rate (CFR) measure. The reason why I have included the Death Rate is that it provides a measure of the efficacy of two things:
Level of testing and ability to find cases - The Infection Fatality Rate (IFR) of COVID-19, which represents the number of people who are infected who die, is estimated to be between 1-2% (Levin et al., 2020). When the CFR is closer to the IFR, it indicates, generally speaking, that a country’s health system is better able to discover and record cases, through higher rates of testing.
Coverage and efficacy of vaccination - In countries with high full vaccination rates, the CFR has dropped significantly. Therefore, the CFR acts as an observable indication of both vaccine efficacy, and vaccine coverage.
Disclaimer - a more accurate ‘rolling’ CFR would have deaths lag cases by a couple of weeks, so the CFR I have included is more of a rough measure of how the CFR is changing month to month.
Findings
Stages of the pandemic
The number of cases and deaths in Panama starts off relatively slowly, peaking initially in July 2020 at just under 32,000 cases and 800 deaths per month (approx. 1,000 cases and 25 deaths per day). This initial peak occurred noticeably later than countries in Europe and North America, likely due to the virus taking longer to seed in countries less connected to global trade/commerce.
Cases and deaths then dipped slightly for a few months, but surged massively in December 2020 - January 2021. This represents the main peak of cases and deaths in Panama. In this two month period, nearly 155,000 cases were reported, and just under 2,200 people died. For a country with a pre-pandemic population of around 4.2 million (United Nations, 2019), this is a huge number in such a short space of time.
Case numbers then dropped markedly, and have followed a similar pattern to what happened in mid-2020 - cases peaked in July 2021 at a very similar level to July 2020.
Analysis of the Death Rate
Generally speaking, the Death Rate in Panama is quite close to the estimated IFR of COVID-19, so the country’s health system has been quite effective at finding and recording cases. The Death Rate was noticeably higher at the beginning of the pandemic, likely due to lower testing, and less experience in treating the disease. The spike in the Death Rate in February 2021 is most likely due to some deaths associated with January’s case spike occurring in February, thereby inflating the Death Rate.
It is clear to see how the Death Rate has dropped in Panama since May 2021. For instance, July 2021 saw a similar number of cases to July 2020, but only 35% the number of deaths. As of late August, over 60% of Panama’s population have received at least one dose of vaccine, and 30% have been fully vaccinated (Ritchie et al., 2021). Vaccinations are clearly pushing down the Death Rate, but Panama has a fair way to go until it’s population has a high level of protection.

The following table is a table of summary statistics, built using the package vtable. I have included summary statistics for the variables Cases, Deaths, and Death Rate (%).

articles.title: Blog Post 2 - Spain and COVID-19
articles.contents:
Introduction This blog post seeks to examine two aspects of the response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Spain - vaccination and public health measures. First, Spain’s vaccination rate is compared to other large European nations, in terms of the overall percentage of those fully vaccinated, and the time at which vaccination rates peaked. Second, the timing of the imposition of public health measures in Spain is compared to the occurrence of spikes in case numbers, and Spain’s public health responses are compared to those of its European neighbours. Data Story 1: Vaccinations The first part of this analysis looks at vaccination rates in Spain compared to its large European neighbours. This involves looking at how full vaccination rates have increased over time, and how the rate of vaccinations per million people have fluctuated daily during 2021. This plot shows that, as of September 2021, Spain is the standout performer among the largest European nations in terms of fully vaccinating its population against COVID-19. Like the other large EU countries, Spain’s vaccination program was initially slower than the UK’s; for instance, by the beginning of June 2021, the UK had fully vaccinated ~40% of its population, compared to ~20% for Spain, France, Italy and Germany. However, Spain’s vaccination program has now raced past the UK’s, as well as exceeding those of the other large EU nations. Spain’s full vaccination rate surpassed the UK’s around late July 2021, and now sits at 75% of the population, which is ~11% higher than the next best-performing country, the UK (64%). This plot also shows how Spain’s vaccination program surged to become arguably the best performing in Europe. In the first months of 2021, Spain’s vaccination program, along with that of its EU contemporaries, was much slower than the UK’s; in February 2021, the UK was vaccinating at more than 4 times the rate of the large EU nations. However, after May 2021, Spain’s rate of new vaccinations surpassed the UK’s, and peaked on 4 July 2021 at 12,363 vaccinations per million, far more than the UK’s peak of 8,830 vaccinations per million on 31 March 2021, and more than Germany’s (10,419, 14 June), France’s (10,297, 21 July), and Italy’s (9,814, 10 June). The result is that Spain now has the most highly vaccinated population out of the large European nations. Overall, it can be seen that, after a relatively slow start when compared to the United Kingdom’s feted vaccine roll-out, Spain’s full vaccination level against COVID-19 is among the highest in Europe, and in the world more widely. This holds Spain in better stead than many nations, at this time, to reduce hospitalisations and deaths from COVID-19. Data Story 2: Public health measures The aim of this section of the analysis is to see at what level of infections Spain increased the stringency of its public health measures, how that varied between 2020 and 2021, and how Spain’s public health measure stringency compared to its large European neighbours. It must be noted that I excluded the first few months of the pandemic from the first plot, as the first wave of infections in Spain was largely not recorded, due to a lack of testing. To explain this plot, it is necessary to first explain how the measure of stringency of public health restrictions is calculated: Stringency index The Stringency index is a composite measure of nine metrics that relate to restrictions on civil society imposed to control the COVID-19 pandemic. The higher the index score, the more restrictive the measures. The nine metrics include: school closures, workplace closures, cancellation of public events, restrictions on public gatherings, closures of public transport, stay-at-home requirements, public information campaigns, restrictions on internal movements, and international travel controls. Different combinations of these can effect the index in different ways - the index score is a rough guide as to how restrictive all the measures collectively are on society. The plot shows that, at the beginning of the time period, Spain was exiting a period of very strict public health measures. This was at the beginning of the pandemic, when there was the first wave of COVID-19 infections, but these were largely not recorded due to a lack of testing. Since then, Spain has experienced three other waves of infection, with peaks in November 2020, January 2021, and July 2021. In the case of the first two of these waves, the Spanish government increased the stringency of public health measures, although not to the same level as the first wave. What stands out is the response to the most recent wave of infections. The Spanish government started to significantly ease restrictions from early May 2021; by the beginning of July, cases were rising sharply. However, the Spanish government did not impose any significant new restrictions in response to this. The reason for this is vaccination; the Spanish population has reached a level of full vaccination where the health system can cope with much larger numbers of cases, as not as many people are being hospitalised with severe illness. This plot shows that Spain, in comparison to other large European nations, has not been any more or less prone to imposing strict public health measures to control COVID case numbers. In the initial phase of the COVID-19 pandemic, beginning in February/March 2020, all of the large European nations imposed very strict public health measures to protect their health systems. Spain enacted its harshest period of restrictions from 30 March 2020 to 5 May 2020. The Spanish government then reduced restrictions to a degree during winter and autumn, but reimposed relatively harsh restrictions at the end of October 2020 (although not to the same level as March-May 2020). Restrictions in Spain were not significantly eased until May 2021, and reached their current level around mid-June (with some small easing after). Spain’s experience is fairly typical of large European nations in general - all five have followed a relatively similar path. What is interesting to see is how the nations are responding in different ways to case levels in 2021, given that all of them have fully vaccinated at least 60% of their population: Spain and the UK have eased restrictions very significantly, to the point where present restrictions are equivalent in stringency to those imposed just before the first national lockdowns in March 2020 (those restrictions were relatively light). Spain and the UK have the highest full vaccination rates of the countries examined here. Germany is maintaining significantly tighter restrictions, tighter than those during the summer of 2020. France and Italy had eased restrictions significantly, but have recently tightened them again to a certain extent. Overall, Spain has followed a similar path to its neighbours in terms of imposing public health measures to protect the health system, and the population more widely. However, as of September 2021, there is evidence that Spain’s particularly high vaccination rate may be allowing it to eschew restrictions to a greater degree than some other European nations.
